As the company name suggests, it is said to be a shrine that enshrines '''{{ill|lt=Ooyatsuhime/Tsumatsuhime|Q10935047|WD=Q10935047|lt=Tsumatsuhime|1=Oyatsuhime and Tsumatsuhime}}''' (Tsumatsuhime no Mikoto, Sakutsuhime no Mikoto) as its enshrined deity.Regarding Tsumatsuhime, it is described in one book in "{{ill|lt=Nihon Shoki|Q813935|WD=Q813935|1=Nihon Shoki}}" that she is the daughter god of {{ill|lt=Susanoo|Q272993|WD=Q272993|lt=Susanoo|1=Susanoo-no-Mikoto}}. Also, the older brother god of Tsumatsuhime is {{ill|lt=Isotakejin|Q10881556|WD=Q10881556|WD=Q10881556|lt=Isotakeru/Itakeru|1=Isotakeru-no-Mikoto}}, and the older sister god is {{ill|lt=Ooyatsuhime/Tsumatsuhime|Q10935047|WD=Q10935047|lt=Oyatsuhime no Mikoto|1=Oyatsuhime and Tsumatsuhime}} ( Both gods are enshrined at {{ill|lt=Itaikiso Shrine|Q11379271|WD=Q11379271|1=Itakiso shrine}} (Itaikiso, Wakayama City) and {{ill|lt=Oyatsuhime Shrine|Q11434556|WD=Q11434556|1=Oyatsuhime Shrine}} (Udamori, Wakayama City), respectively. These three deities are said to be the gods who brought tree species to Kii Province, and in Kii they are collectively known as ``''Itaiki Sosanjin'' {{Sfn|Takazumi Shrine (Taira)|1983}}.

=== History ===

==== Outline ====
The first reference to the historical material is the article in "{{ill|lt=Shoku Nihongi|Q611399|WD=Q611399|1=Shoku Nihongi}}" {{ill|lt=Taiho (Japan)|Q1346269|WD=Q1346269|lt=Taiho|1=Taihō (era)}} 2nd year ({{ill|lt=702|Q23497|WD=Q23497|1=702}})<ref group="original">"Shoku Nihongi" article dated February 22, 702. In </ref>, there is an article about the separation of the three shrines of Ita-Kiso, Oya-Tohime, and Toma-Tohime.{{Sfn|Takazumi Shrine (Taira)|1983}}.

"Shinsho Kaku Chofusho" {{ill|lt=Daido (Japan)|Q1373191|WD=Q1373191|lt=Daido|1=Daidō}} 1st year ({{ill|lt=806|Q30021|WD=Q30021|1=806}})<ref group="原">"Shinsho Kakuchofusho" 10 (Shinji Shoke Fudo) Daido 1st year (806). In </ref>, 13 houses were given to ``Tomazuhime no Kami'' of Kii Province {{Sfn|Takazumi Shrine (Taira)|1983}}. Related, {{ill|lt=Shohei (Japan)|Q1324874|WD=Q1324874|lt=Shohei|1=Jōhei}} ({{ill|lt=931|Q24789|WD=Q24789|1=931}}-{{ill|lt=938|Q24794|WD=Q24794|1=938}}) "{{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Japanese name Ruijusho|1=UNKNOWN}}', ``Tsuma (Tsuma) Go'' is seen in Kii Province {{ill|lt=Nakusa District|Q11415547|WD=Q11415547|1=Nagusa district}}, which is said to mean ``Tsuma Kobe'' {{Sfn|Takazumi Shrine (Taira)|1983}}.As {{ill|lt=Divine|Q11591025|WD=Q11591025|1=Shinkai (divine rank)}}, {{ill|lt=Jōkan (Japan)|Q1075635|WD=Q1075635|lt=Jōkan|1=Jōgan}} In the first year of the year ({{ill|lt=859|Q23897|WD=Q23897|1=859}}), he was promoted to the lower rank of Jushii (junior fourth rank) as ``Shinto Matsuhime'' along with Itagesojin and Ōyatsuhime no kami {{Sfn|Takazumi Shrine (Taira)|1983}}.

{{ill|lt=Extension (era name)|Q1327274|WD=Q1327274|lt=Extension|1=Enchō}} 5 years ({{ill|lt=927|Q30470|WD=Q30470|1=927}}) "{{ill|lt=Engishiki|Q1342448|WD=Q1342448|1=Engishiki}}" {{ill|lt=Engishiki Shinmyocho|Q11064932|WD=Q11064932|lt=Shinmyocho|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō}} states that in Nagusa District, Kii Province, there are "Tomatohime Shrine Meishindai It will be listed at {{ill|lt=Meishin Taisha|Q9610964|WD=Q9610964|1=Myōjin Taisha}} as ``Monthly New Year'' and {{ill|lt=Monthly Festival|Q11516161|WD=Q11516161|1=Tsukinami-no-Matsuri}} and {{jalink| It is written that it was kept in {{ill|lt=heihaku|Q11481885|WD=Q11481885|1=Hanpei}} at Niinamesai|Q11501518}}{{Sfn|Takazumi Shrine (Taira)|1983}}. In ``{{ill|lt=Kiokuni Shinmecho|Q17210008|WD=Q17210008|1=Kii no Kuni Jinmyō-chō}}'', the Tenjin is listed as ``Junior Fourth Rank Upper Tumatsu Hime Okami'', and it is different from Itaukeso Okami, who rose to Shoichi Rank (Shoichi Rank), and has an open shrine {{Sfn|Takazumi Shrine (Taira)|1983}}. In addition, in the same book, there is also a related entry of ``Junior Fourth Rank, Lower Tsumutohime no Okami.''

Its subsequent history is unclear, and there are various theories as to which shrine the above shrine belongs to.

==== God level ====
* Records of {{ill|lt=Divine rank|Q11591025|WD=Q11591025|1=Shinkai (divine rank)}} dedication in the history of the Six Kingdoms
** {{ill|lt=Jogan (Japan)|Q1075635|WD=Q1075635|lt=Jogan|1=Jōgan}} On the 27th of the first month of the first year ({{ill|lt=859|Q23897|WD=Q23897|1=859}}), the rank of Jufifth Rank, Lower Rank, Eighth Grade to Junior Fourth Rank, Lower Rank, Eighth Grade (``{{ill|lt=Nihon Sandai Jitsuroku|Q1052981|WD=Q1052981|1=Nihon Sandai Jitsuroku}}'') - The notation is ``Shinto Matsuhime God''.
* After Six Kingdoms History
** Upper Juichii (``{{ill|lt=Kiokuni Shinto Name Book|Q17210008|WD=Q17210008|1=Kii no Kuni Jinmyō-chō}}'') - Written as ``Tomato Hime Okami.'' Is it a typo in "Junior Fourth Rank Upper"?

=== Historical evidence ===
The exact location of Shikinai Shrine ``Tomatsu Hime Shrine'' is still uncertain. In ancient times, it is identified as Miyako Matsuhime Shrine (Kichirei, (1)) in Shandong in the "Kiokuni Famous Places Zue" and "Nanki Shrine Record" ({{ill|lt=Enkyo|Q1183728|WD=Q1183728|1=Enkyō (Edo period)}}3 ({{ill|lt=1746|Q7589|WD=Q7589|1=1746}})).

Furthermore, in ``{{ill|lt=Kii Zoku Fudoki|Q11604964|WD=Q11604964|1=Kii Zoku Fudoki}}'', it is said that Matsuhime Shrine (1), the capital of Shandong, which is mentioned in ``Nanki Shrine Roku'', was originally dedicated to ``Yoshire Tsuhime no Mikoto'' {{Sfn|Takazumi Shrine (Taira)|1983}}. Yoshiretsuhime-no-Mikoto appears in the ``Kiokuni Jinmyocho'' as ``Junior Fifth Rank Lower, Yoshiretsu Hime-no-Kami.'' In addition, in "Zoku Fudoki", there is a theory that Hirao's wife Daimyo Shrine (currently Tomatohime Shrine, (2)) is referred to as ``Toumatsuhime Shrine'' {{Sfn|Takazumi Shrine (Taira)|1983}}.

One of these theories is that {{ill|lt=Water theory|Q2464727|WD=Q2464727|1=Water conflict}} ({{ill|lt=Water theory of Szene-Kunikake Shrine and Kodaimyojin|Q11504966|WD=Q11504966|1=Water theory of Szene-Kunikake Shrine and Kodaimyojin}}) that occurred between {{ill|lt=Maezen Shrine/Kokukake Shrine|Q888184|WD=Q888184|1=Hinokuma Shrine}} and Wasaso. |Q1193059}}5 ({{ill|lt=1433|Q6356|WD=Q6356|1=1433}}) states that Takazumi Shrine (3) was originally located in Maemiya, and later moved its enshrined place to Shandong, and later to Mt. Wasa.{{Sfn|Takazumi Shrine (Taira)|1983}}. Since this legend is consistent with an article written in 702 in the ``Shoku Nihongi'', ``Zoku Fudoki'' states that there is a high possibility that Takazumi Shrine is Tomatohime Shrine {{Sfn|Takazumi Shrine (Taira)|1983}}.

