=== History ===
{{ill|lt=Kiokuni|Q864053|WD=Q864053|1=Kii Province}}{{ill|lt=Meishin Taisha|Q9610964|WD=Q9610964|1=Myōjin Taisha}} "Tomatsu Hime Shrine" in {{ill|lt=Nakusa District|Q11415547|WD=Q11415547|1=Nagusa district}} {{ill|lt=Ronsha|Q135022904|WD=Q135022904|1=Shikinai Ronsha}}. This is compared to our company in "Ki Province Meisho Zue" and "Nanki Shrine Record" ({{ill|lt=Enkyo|Q1183728|WD=Q1183728|1=Enkyō (Edo period)}}3 ({{ill|lt=1746|Q7589|WD=Q7589|1=1746}})). On the other hand, "Zoku Fudoki" denies this, and our company says that it is a shrine that enshrines the "Junior Fifth Rank Lower Yoshiretsuhime-no-kami" that appears in the "Kiokuni Jinmyocho", and compares Matsumatsuhime-kami to Takazumi Shrine.

According to the shrine statement book, our company was dedicated as Shikinai Shrine ``Miyatomatsuhime Shrine'' during the Edo period, but in {{ill|lt=Meiji|Q3125096|WD=Q3125096|1=Meiji era}} it was renamed to ``Yoshiretsuhime Shrine'' {{Sfn|Miyatomatsu Hime Shrine (Shikiuchi Shrine)|1987|p=51-52}}. In the 6th year of the Meiji era ({{ill|lt=1873|Q7757|WD=Q7757|1=1873}}), it was ranked as {{ill|lt=village shrine|Q134917284|WD=Q134917284|1=Son-sha}} in the {{ill|lt=modern shrine rank system|Q712534|WD=Q712534|lt=old shrine rank|1=Modern system of ranked Shinto shrines}}. After that, in {{ill|lt=Showa|Q327567|WD=Q327567|1=Shōwa era}}21 ({{ill|lt=1946|Q18610|WD=Q18610|1=1946}}), it reverted to its former name ``Miyakomatsuhime Shrine'' and remains the current name.

